'''''Yoda: Dark Rendezvous''''' is a [[Star Wars Legends|''Star Wars'' Legends]] novel written by [[Sean Stewart]]. It is a part of the [[Clone Wars multimedia project|''Clone Wars'' multimedia project]], and it was first published by [[Del Rey]] on [[November 23]], [[2004]], along with an [[Yoda: Dark Rendezvous (abridged audiobook)|abridged]] version. An [[Yoda: Dark Rendezvous (unabridged audiobook)|unabridged]] version of the audiobook was released on [[January 23]], [[2024]] as part of ''[[The Essential Legends Collection]]''.

==Publisher's summary==
''The savage Clone Wars have forced the Republic to the edge of collapse. During the height of battle, one Jedi Knight escapes the carnage to deliver a message to Yoda on Coruscant. It appears that Dooku wants peace and demands a rendezvous. Chances are slim that the treacherous Count is sincere, but with a million lives at stake, Yoda has no choice.''

''The meeting will take place on Vjun, a planet steeped in evil. The challenge could not be more difficult. Can Yoda win back his once promising pupil from the dark side, or will Count Dooku unleash his sinister forces against his former mentor? Either way, Yoda is sure of one thing: This battle will be one of the fiercest he'll ever face.''

==Plot summary==
The Clone Wars rage across [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]]. [[Grand Master/Legends|Grand Master]] Yoda receives a message from his former [[Padawan/Legends|Padawan]], Count Dooku. In the message, Dooku concedes that the conflict has gotten out of hand and that he is willing to come to a truce. Dooku invites Yoda to meet him on the planet Vjun, where they will organize the cease-fire. After conferring with his fellow [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Masters]] from the [[Jedi Council/Legends|Council]], Yoda decides that the chance to end the war outweighs the perils of a trap.

To cover for the secret meeting, the [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] contract famous [[Actor/Legends|actor]] and Yoda impersonator [[Palleus Chuff]] to act as a decoy while Yoda departs for Vjun. Disguised as Yoda, Chuff leaves on a publicized mission to [[Ithor/Legends|Ithor]]. However, upon Chuff's arrival at Ithor, his [[Starship/Legends|ship]] is ambushed and destroyed by [[Asajj Ventress/Legends|Asajj Ventress]], who was seeking to [[Assassin/Legends|assassinate]] the Jedi Master. Yoda's perceived death is a significant blow to the Republic's morale. Meanwhile, Yoda travels to Vjun, accompanied by Jedi Masters [[Jai Maruk]] and [[Maks Leem]] and their Padawans, "[[Tallisibeth Enwandung-Esterhazy|Scout]]" and [[Whie Malreaux/Legends|Whie]].

During a [[Spaceport/Legends|spaceport]] layover, Ventress, accompanied by the bumbling but brave Chuff, manages to catch the quintet and unleashes a dangerous new type of [[Battle droid/Legends|battle droid]]. While the other Jedi fight the [[Droid/Legends|droids]] and Ventress, Yoda seeks to rescue Chuff. Both Maruk and Leem fall to the droids and Ventress. Yoda, however, manages to divert Ventress's attention, and the three Jedi escape with Chuff in tow.

On Vjun, Count Dooku awaits Yoda in the [[Château Malreaux]], the manor of the long-since waned aristocratic [[House Malreaux]]. As the Jedi land on Vjun, they are forced to separate. Yoda goes to meet with Dooku, and the Padawans follow a mysterious disruption felt in [[The Force/Legends|the Force]]. The Padawans are captured by Ventress. She reveals to Whie that he is a member of House Malreaux, and the insane [[Lady/Legends|Lady]] [[Whirry Malreaux]] is his [[Parent/Legends|mother]]. Ventress holds Scout in a tight Force grip and tries to bring Whie to the dark side of the Force. Whie is able to resist.

Meanwhile, Yoda meets with Dooku. They engage in a debate about the Force and reminiscence about Dooku's childhood at the [[Jedi Temple/Legends|Jedi Temple]]. Yoda encourages his former apprentice to leave the dark side and [[Palpatine/Legends|Darth Sidious]] forever. Dooku is emotionally stirred, and Whirry arrives with news: [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]] and [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] have arrived at the mansion, having been dispatched by the Jedi Council.

Convinced that the legendary duo are replacements for him, Dooku is overcome by jealousy and throws Whirry out of a window. Yoda saves her and begins a duel with Dooku. Dooku activates an orbital missile targeted at the house and escapes with Ventress. Yoda succeeds in stopping the missile. With Kenobi, Skywalker, and the Padawans, Yoda returns to Coruscant. Elsewhere, Dooku laments the knowledge that everyone he had ever loved, including Yoda, has forsaken him.

==Development==
The hardcover [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]] novels published between [[Wikipedia:2003|2003]] and [[Wikipedia:2005|2005]] focused on major [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] characters - [[Mace Windu/Legends|Mace Windu]], [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]], [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] – while the paperbacks were intended to give supporting characters like [[Barriss Offee/Legends|Barriss Offee]] and [[Clone commando/Legends|clone commandos]] a spotlight. It seems surprising, then, that [[Yoda/Legends|Yoda’s]] sole starring role in a ''[[Star Wars]]'' novel should be in a paperback original. ''Yoda: Dark Rendezvous'' arrived as a replacement novel for ''[[Escape from Dagu]]'', a canceled paperback that was to have focused on [[Shaak Ti/Legends|Shaak Ti]]. Author [[Sean Stewart]] made his participation in Star Wars novels contingent on being able to write a Yoda story, a rare exception to [[Lucasfilm]]'s policy keeping his character reserved. This novel is unique in its exploration of the psychology and motivations of characters such as Yoda and [[Dooku/Legends|Dooku]].<ref name="Essential Reader's Companion" />

==Continuity==
''Yoda: Dark Rendezvous'' is a part of the [[Clone Wars multimedia project|''Clone Wars'' multimedia project]]. The ''Clone Wars'' timeline contained within ''Dark Rendezvous'' dates the events of the novel to thirty [[Standard month/Legends|months]] after the [[First Battle of Geonosis/Legends|Battle of Geonosis]], following the events of ''[[Jedi Trial]]'' and preceding the events of ''[[Boba Fett: A New Threat]]''. However, this timeline was [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] by the animated television series ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'', and a cohesive timeline has not been described.

Supporting character [[Whie Malreaux/Legends|Whie Malreaux]] is actually a background [[Padawan/Legends|Padawan]] from the [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith]] movie (2005). Malreaux’s prophetic and confusing [[Force vision/Legends|visions]] of being [[Death/Legends|killed]] by a Jedi come true when [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]], fallen to the [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|dark side]], kills him during the [[Operation: Knightfall/Legends|assault on the Jedi Temple]].<ref name="Essential Reader's Companion" />

